A black box in the car?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the decaying highway system, and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that can be found in the dashboard of any car.
The devices that record every kilometre driven and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state’s planning offices to revise the outdated system of financing U.S. roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the kilometres travelled – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax receipts.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a move, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently looking at how to switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is truly a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’re just potentially going to use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments, which plans to record miles driven among all California drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for this is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is bankrupt.
In America, however, fuel is not as much as it used to be.
Cars consume less gasoline.
The state mineral oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 cents per litre) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians do not dare to raise the tax even by a penny at high fuel prices.
“The gasoline tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a traffic legislation expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state has recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
Not surprisingly, the idea is appealing to urban liberals, as the tax could be used, for example, to influence driving behaviour in such a way as to reduce congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases.
The Californian planners are relying on the system to develop strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined goals on climate change.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also inspired by the idea of having drivers pay for the distance covered.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” explains Adrian Moore, vice president of guidelines at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers who, in a 2011 report, had urged Congress to move toward mile-based settlement.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the move, responding to the concerns of MEPs from rural areas who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the petroleum tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois is testing it with trucks to a limited extent.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, drivers were skeptical about the idea that the government could track any of their movements.
“Concerns about Big Brother and things like that were a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and earnings management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to track the miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
So, according to Khan, the public would be more reassured.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company originally did not start to help states tax drivers.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging automotive insurance market, where drivers should pay based on the miles travelled.
But the devices she tested are also interesting for the road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information, which is regularly uploaded by modem.
“People are more willing to get involved if their speed and locations are not recorded,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programs.
There are significantly cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving drivers a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose no device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents of the state.
Others hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that can also be used to pay parking fees, pay insurance only for kilometers driven, and collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, which allows drivers to avoid traffic jams.
“Automobilists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits the system offers,” the city’s planning document says.
However, some traffic planners wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-time fee or an annual fee could be imposed on drivers with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little gasoline, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is enough," said Randy Rentschler, the Commission's head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers worry about their privacy and many other things.
