Esa decides on large space missions: missions for billions
Faraway planets, gravitational waves or black holes – experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they intend to launch in the coming years.
Thirty proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far Worlds.
More than 1,000 planets at other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should one search for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or searching for Earth-like planets and perhaps discovering extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions that are being asked by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are intended to advance research decisively.
The budget for such "L-missions" is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space exploration met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
Thirty ideas were discussed, five of which have now been shortlisted.
Numerous committees review the proposals, hook up with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision is to be made by the Scientific Program Committee.
In total, the ESA has selected four major questions to be answered by the missions of the Cosmic Vision program initiated in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
In order to investigate this question, the Cheops Space Telescope will be launched in 2017, with which 500 already known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity will be studied in more detail.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could map Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to be an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to shed light on the preconditions for the emergence of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied exemplarily.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved a mission of the M-Class (there the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is set to launch in 2017 and monitor the surface and activity of the Sun closely.
Jupiter and its moons are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the ESA envisages the first of the three L-missions of the Cosmic Vision program.
The Juice (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is expected to study the planet's atmosphere as well as the icy moons Europe, Callisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature known to us are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also deviations that could show the physicists the way to a new theory, under the umbrella of which all known laws of nature can be combined.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, which consists of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and galaxy clusters together, and dark energy, whose action accelerates the expansion of the universe.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of a second of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy are.
With "Euclid", the ESA has already approved an M-mission, whose launch is scheduled for 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe will investigate the distribution of matter in the universe throughout the sky for the first time, enabling conclusions about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best chance of obtaining an L-mission is "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for the detection of gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
Elisa could do this, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission provides a two- or three-probe detector that is stationed in space.
In contrast to systems on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that were created during the Big Bang, thus providing new insights into the formation of the cosmos.
Four more proposals are competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which will explore black holes, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the Solar System, "Prism", a mission to survey the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder", which will investigate and track Earth-like planets.
Proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the Moon, Venus and asteroids as well as for solar physics have already been eliminated.
