Relations between the United States and Germany are burdened by claims that the NSA has intercepted the cell phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Thomas Oppermann, the MP who heads the parliamentary committee responsible for intelligence, said that the opportunity should be seized to hear Snowden as a witness if possible, “without endangering him and completely ruining relations with the United States.”
Ströbele, a Green MP, posted a picture of himself and Snowden in his Twitter feed.
During his visit to Russia, he was accompanied by two German journalists.
Ströbele explained that according to the lawyer of former NSA employee Snowden could not return to Russia if he left the country.
If Snowden testifies in Germany, then he needs an assurance that he is “safe” there, the MP said.
Snowden said in his letter that he faced a “serious and ongoing” persecution campaign that drove him out of his homeland.
However, he was touched by the worldwide reaction to “my act of political expression.”
Citizens around the world, as well as high-ranking politicians – including in the United States – have described the revelations about an uncontrolled system of comprehensive surveillance as a merit to the general public.
In his letter, Snowden makes an offer to the German authorities to cooperate “when the difficulties surrounding the humanitarian situation have been resolved.”
Frontier Airlines charges for carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to demand up to $100 from passengers who want to store hand luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a piece of hand luggage and $2 for coffee or lemonade, even though it was stated in the announcement on Wednesday that passengers would be allowed to keep the whole can.
The new fee applies to hand luggage in the luggage compartment above the seat, small bags below the seat are still free.
Frontier said it would charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance, and $100 for travelers who only paid at the gateway.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee was aimed at moving travelers to take care of the payment in advance.
"We don't want to calculate this sum," she explained.
Airlines began charging for the first and second checked baggage in 2008.
Passengers who tried to circumvent this have therefore stuffed as much as possible into hand luggage, resulting in the luggage compartments above the seat being often overcrowded.
Fees are a way of encouraging passengers to take less on board.
O'Malley said the new fee isn't really about making money.
It concerns Frontier’s most loyal customers, who have clearly stated that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy your tickets on the airline’s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger may be allowed to carry a piece of luggage free of charge at Frontier’s gateway, but the next person will have to pay $100 for a comparable piece of luggage.
O’Malley said Frontier’s website and check-in procedures would be changed so that passengers would be informed of the fee before arriving at the gate.
Frontier’s new carry-on baggage fee will only come into effect in the summer, with no exact date yet.
Passengers often gossip about baggage surcharges and other charges, but airlines like to rely on them.
They argue that carrying the baggage costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they wished it.
Many on Wall Street see the new baggage charges as a sign that airlines are raising enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most people have so far avoided hand luggage fees.
Three years ago, Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge for hand luggage, and later followed Allegiant Air, another low-cost airline.
The only other airline with such a fee is the Hungarian Wizz Air, said airline advisor Jay Sorensen, who is closely monitoring the additional fees.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the hand luggage fee raised Spirit $50 million annually.
Sorensen, who previously held a leadership position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew with Spirit and was curious about what would expect him at the gateway if passengers were faced with the company’s unusual carry-on baggage fee.
“The boarding process was one of the smoothest I’ve experienced in my aviation career,” he said.
I expected to see teeth grinding and hand-to-hand discussions at the gateway.
“The plane was full,” he explained, “and the boarding was running like lubricated.”
Frontier also follows Spirit with the $2, which are required for coffee, tea, lemonade or juice.
The company stated that passengers who bought lemonade or juice would be allowed to keep the whole can and coffee would be refilled free of charge.
Water is still free.
US Airways had briefly tried to demand money for soft drinks in 2008, but reversed it seven months later after passengers complained and no other large company had followed.
Frontiers’ step to charge hand luggage fees if passengers do not buy directly from the airline is the most recent initiative aimed at directing customers to its own website.
Airlines pay online travel agencies such as Orbitz $10 to $25 per ticket sold.
This provides all companies with an incentive to move passengers to buy directly from them instead of through an online travel agency.
Frontier, however, has gone the farthest in this area.
In September, the company began to award half as many frequent flyer miles when booking through an online travel agency.
On Wednesday, the miles were reduced again to 25 percent of the flight route.
An air trip booked with a third-party provider with Frontier over 1000 miles therefore only earns customers 250 miles.
Passengers can also reserve seats exclusively for direct purchases on Frontier’s website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base at its Denver headquarters, but the business is shrinking and the company is losing money.
Revenue declined by 9 percent and flight capacity shrunk by just under 13 percent in the first quarter, according to the financial report released Wednesday by the parent company, Republic Airways Holdings Inc.
Republic has tried to control Frontier’s finances as part of the company’s sale.
