Bombardier losses after decrease in delivery numbers and orders
Canadian aircraft and rail manufacturer Bombardier Inc. reported a 15 percent drop in net profit on Thursday, after it was under pressure from declining orders and deliveries on aircraft in the third quarter, as well as contract problems in the rail business.
Bombardier, based in Montreal, also did not release flight test data for its brand new CSeries aircraft and did not provide any new information on whether the aircraft could go into commercial use next September, according to the ambitious schedule.
Up to now, only three more launches have followed the test aircraft’s maiden flight one and a half months ago, which makes it questionable whether the test phase is going as planned.
Results lagged behind forecasts, leading to a price drop of over eight percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, lowered his valuation on Thursday from “outperform” to “sector perform” in view of the stock’s limited price potential over the next one to two quarters.
"While weaker delivery figures were largely expected for aircraft, we are clearly disappointed by the development of the margin in the transport sector," Doerksen said in a customer letter.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries as the aircraft test program progresses.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes that the CSeries aircraft series will catapult the company into the lower market segment, which is currently dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled to the public in March and flew for the first time in September after months of delays.
But so far, binding orders for the CSeries with 177 are moderate as potential buyers want to wait for the results of the flight tests and see if the company’s claims regarding fuel efficiency and cost savings potential of the new jet airliner are true.
Currently, there are a total of 403 orders and commitments from 15 customers and companies.
CEO Pierre Beaudoin is confident that Bombardier will achieve its target of 300 binding orders at the start of commercial use of the jet.
The management also assured analysts and media on Thursday that the program was on schedule.
"The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected," Beaudoin said at a conference call, adding that during the aircraft's service life, ground tests and software updates were scheduled.
Every manufacturer plans differently.
We decided to take a first flight and then add a review period, which we did.
This happens throughout the flight program.
The second of five test aircraft is expected to launch in the coming weeks, the remaining shortly afterwards, the company said.
Nevertheless, analysts remain skeptical about whether the first customer can commission a CSeries aircraft twelve months after the maiden flight.
Bombardier said it is reviewing commissioning planning (EIS) and will update it in the coming months.
“The slow progress of the flight test – although obviously in line with Bombardier’s internal planning – reinforces our view that commissioning is delayed to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier's net profit fell to $147 million, or 8 cents per share, from $172 million, or 9 cents per share, the previous year.
Adjusted earnings per share remain unchanged at 9 cents.
Sales declined slightly, falling from 4.2 to 4.1 billion dollars.
Analysts expected a profit of 10 cents per share and revenue of $4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I/B/E/S.
The world’s fourth largest aircraft manufacturer says it delivered 45 aircraft this quarter, down from 57 last year.
Net orders fell from 83 aircraft to 26.
The order backlog in the aerospace division was $32.9 billion on September 30, unchanged from December 31.
"In the aerospace sector, the results were in line with our targets, but the low order intake and overall market conditions were disappointing," said Beaudoin.
Sales in the aerospace sector fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world’s largest railway manufacturer, announced that revenue in this segment has increased by just under 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
The order backlog in the transport division was $32.6 billion on September 30, slightly up from December 31.
The profit margin in the transport sector was affected by settlement problems in some major contracts.
According to management, there will be new targets for the fourth quarter.
In the afternoon trading on Thursday, Bombardier shares declined by 8.5 percent and stood at 4.83 Canadian dollars, after it was also announced that Google’s Chief Financial Officer Patrick Pichette will join the board.
Brazilian Embraer SA, the world’s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and Bombardier’s closest rival, reported a 10 percent drop in quarterly earnings on Thursday.
