Cocaine-dependent lawyer who warned drug boss about police investigation must go to jail
Basharat Ditta, 42, shared information to underworld size Neil Scarborough
The lawyer feared his secret drug addiction could come to light
He was sentenced to three years in prison by the Liverpool Crown Court.
A well-known criminal defense attorney who warned a drug lord about a major police investigation because he was afraid his secret drug addiction could be revealed, was sentenced to three years in prison.
Basharat Ditta, 42, provided underworld giant Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about investigations into his drug trafficking activities after he was compromised by his own cocaine addiction.
The lawyer, nicknamed "Bash" by criminals, was arrested at his home in 2011 after police monitored Scarborough, whom he had represented in a previous drug trial.
Officials watched Scarborough, 32, deliver three bags of cocaine to the attorney’s home in Blackburn, Lancashire, while he was with colleagues at a bar dinner.
Investigations revealed that Ditta regularly consumed Class A drugs after tests found traces of cocaine in his hair, wallet, and credit cards.
Over a period of eight months between January and August 2011, he attempted to obtain unauthorized information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners.
All four suspects were then monitored by police as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire, Cumbria, Merseyside, Berkshire and West Yorkshire.
Together with 32 other people, they were later arrested after police secured <0xC2><0xA3>1.5 million worth of heroin and cocaine and <0xC2><0xA3>200,000 worth of cash in a series of house searches.
Ditta, 42, shared information with the criminals because he feared his drug addiction could become public.
Today, Ditta, who works for the Forbes Solicitors firm in Blackburn, was found guilty and convicted at the Liverpool Crown Court after a three-week trial in two counts of obstruction of justice.
He admitted to cocaine possession in an earlier interview.
The lawyer was convicted after police found out in their investigation of Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011.
Two investigators followed the suspect and saw him go to Ditta’s house and put the 60 percent purity drugs in a black golf glove under the lawyer’s trash can.
Shortly after delivering the drugs, Scarborough regularly phoned Ditta, who was at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park at dinner.
The lawyer returned home, fetched the drugs and then nine messages were exchanged between the two.
In court, it was reported that Ditta was a “regular consumer” of cocaine after tests had discovered class A drugs in his hair, wallet, and credit cards.
Ditta was later arrested, but denied taking cocaine, saying he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client, claiming that their discussion was subject to “attorney secrecy.”
During his arrest, Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards, but they were seized and a hair sample was taken from him.
During the police interrogation, he stated that he was running an office both at his home address and at the workplace and clients would call him at home for legal matters.
In court, it was reported that he had called key drug traffickers, some of whom he had previously represented, after significant arrests and informed them about what the investigators knew about them.
Prosecutor Anne Whyte said, “A criminal attorney should know better than anyone else that you don’t break the law.”
Ditta is accused of abusing his position as a criminal defense attorney because he has been too involved with certain clients.
The relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer, but a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs.
Some of his communications were undoubtedly legitimate, for he was the lawyer of these persons.
But that went far beyond the boundaries of a normal relationship between lawyer and client.
He countered the police investigation as much as possible so that they could continue to pursue their criminal activities.
Mr. Ditta thus discredited his profession.
He was too close to certain clients, especially Scarborough, and he allowed his independence to be compromised.
Ditta denied any wrongdoing, claiming, “If I were a corrupt lawyer, which I am not, and wanted to pass information to Scarborough, I would not wait 15 hours but would do so immediately.”
But after the hearing, Superintendent Lee Halstead of Lancashire Police said: “Mr. Ditta took the step from a criminal lawyer to a criminal at the moment he began to acquire drugs from organized criminals.”
His addiction to cocaine led to a hopeless compromise and made him receptive to the motives of leading members of organized crime, who commissioned him to obtain valuable information about police investigations.
Lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure public trust and confidence.
Ditta has betrayed this trust and tried to hide behind the facade of his profession.
Lancashire’s Serious and Organised Crime Unit led the investigation into Ditta, which also led to a conviction in three cases for possession of cocaine and obstruction of justice, underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice.
This case should be a warning to criminals and shows that no one can escape the arm of the law.
We'll find you and take you to court.
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after he declared himself guilty of conspiracy to trade heroin, cocaine and cannabis.
Thirty-five other persons involved in the drug trade were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug offences.
On his website, Ditta published an area of questions and answers about himself, stating that his dream job was to represent clients in the death row in America as a lawyer, that his ultimate guest at dinner was Mohammed Ali and that inequality was the motivation for his work.
