Renamo was once a notorious rebel movement initially supported by White-ruled Rhodesia and later South Africa’s apartheid government in an effort to destabilize the country’s independent government.
After the 1992 peace treaty, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe the country is unlikely to fall back into a full-blown conflict, but recent events have worried foreign investors and locals.
Much is at stake for the fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge offshore gas reserves and coal storage in the northwest could bring investments of over $50 billion from companies such as Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US into the country in the coming years.
The ruling Frelimo party, the dominant force since 1975, and Renamo blame each other for the tensions.
Renamo claims the government provoked the recent clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala, a traditional stronghold of Renamos, on 17 October.
The attacks on the former rebels escalated as government troops attacked Renamo bases and attempted to kill Afonso Dhlakama, the group’s leader, Renamos spokesman told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for the clashes and accuses the organization of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has tried to minimize concerns about instability.
