George Kerevan: European unbundling gives Scots a choice
A new day, a new horror story about independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is required to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
This provides the keyword for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a barbed wire-secured border along the Hadrian's Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde proposal pointed out the potential economic benefits that more freedom of movement would entail in the rest of Europe, but as expected, this did not matter in the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more favorable for them.
Since Scotland is currently not part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance for Brussels would be only a small concession in return for what one really wants from the Scots.
Actually not a story.
And one that has come so far that it already resembles a fossil: the first time I heard the "independence means passport controls" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient story.
Why should you expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why exchange the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great plan for the unification of Europe, conceived after the war, has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro as a common currency overboard are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to win almost five million votes in the September federal election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in conjunction with the coercive jacket, into which the respective national economies are forced by sticking to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The crisis of the euro has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and German politicians would like to keep that way.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe will find itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and monetary problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of Brussels’ ‘green’ energy directives – a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas compared to the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s payroll regulations do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is emerging, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, the political elite of France saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany at bay and to raise Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed on Europe its own economic policy, with which the struggling French economy is struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive by-election and thus put the ruling socialists in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with her newly gained popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties perform well in these elections – and this is very possible – then such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
This is the point to which I want to go: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will rather become something like the “Europe of (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of flattering the US.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the final analysis) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put themselves where.
I suspect Scotland could do quite well in a looser European network, as long as we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similarly thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to get an austerity policy imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
Early puberty: growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible.
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be worried if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics Association this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and constituted a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time calming my parents – usually this is not a sign that puberty is coming fast,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious indications of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, as well as body odor, appear earlier in girls.
Nevertheless, there has only been a slight shift in the age of the menarche over the past 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
“When breast development begins, it still takes at least two to three years to menarche,” said Kaplowitz, also author of the book “Early puberty in girls: the essential guide to dealing with this common problem”.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial what is actually the beginning of puberty, but it is "early ripe" if breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnates – something that a pediatrician can closely monitor.
With faster progress, tests by an endicronologist may be recommended so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatments for delaying early menstruation and defending against another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to inhibition of growth and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the rate of development, the rate of growth and the emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings, unlike being their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply do not want their very young daughters to have the period.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side,” Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days at ten.
Even though there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was emotionally unprepared.
She came home frightened and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many widely published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foodstuffs, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media would be the cause.
Boys get into puberty much earlier than girls.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported the conduct of a 2001 study on girls aged six to nine, which establishes a link between body fat and puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to have been affected by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend to a full-blown earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and young children.
“We need to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean that you have to have a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need assurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than expected.
