“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried and tested all the methods available on the market, but have experienced that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information needed to produce nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt down the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from experiencing nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal levels of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a “time off,” the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, as it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for humans, if it is completely safe, could be given to children before they are tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, however, is that smokers would use it to quit.
“They know then that when they start smoking again, they don’t enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them quit the habit,” he explains.
