The decision affects U.S. companies differently depending on the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate wireless interference from mobile devices, and modify manuals, training materials, carry-on luggage programs, and customer instruction.
“After an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lighter electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any height,” the FAA said in a statement.
In rare cases of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off the equipment during landing.
