Pawning houses boom in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawnshop at the Bendemeer shopping mall in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bangle, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay the school fees of her daughters.
“My husband and I just bought a house, and all my money is in it,” says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns $3,000 each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not sufficient, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is on the rise – is so high that ValueMax, where it traded, became the third pawn house listed on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Bonding jewelry is not only a quick way to get money – 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, Singapore pawn houses require an effective annual rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent required by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
Pfandhäuser, however, offer the advantage that no verification of creditworthiness or income proofs are required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
That’s why millions of people in the region are turning to pawn houses after families feel pressured by rising living costs as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to loose fiscal policies in the developed economies, low- and middle-income families are looking for pawnshops to offset the difference in stuttering economies.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor’s described growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks’ creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product, according to the agency.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80 percent of GDP, an increase of 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has just emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a persistent export weakness and a decline in consumer demand.
“In the end, in the face of rising costs, this means that middle-to-lower segment (the income scale) people will try to supplement their income wherever possible,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historical highs in gold prices over the past two years have intensified the trend to pledge personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city state’s 200 pawnhouses are gold.
People say to themselves, “The gold price looks good, let’s pledge Grandma’s gold chain and get it back next month.”
The largest Thai pawn house operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent growth in its stores in recent months.
The growth in the pawning business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 more in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company finances this with 60 percent of the $66 million it took with the IPO in Singapore this week.
While some lenders have fallen into a crossfire due to high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawn houses not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also do not directly increase debt.
"Customers borrow items they already own, and liquefaction of personal valuables does not increase household education," she explains.
The pawn lending business is increasingly accepted socially as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawn loans are in financial trouble.
Rich people from Singapore also come to ValueMax stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
We have customers from all walks of life.
“This includes wealthy people who borrow something for a business or investment in the short term, or small businesses who need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,” says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
