FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but don’t make cell phone calls)
From departure to landing, passengers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not to make phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the U.S. on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they will be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and equipment storage regulations in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could very soon approve the extended use of electronic devices,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers need to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
You are not allowed to restart it until the aircraft reaches a height of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
Upon landing, passengers must turn them off again and must not take off again until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional flight attendants’ professional association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is safely implemented – and we work closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
Honestly, we are tired of having to feel like watchmen on this issue.
Internet connections for browsing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data below three kilometers were still prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices in flight mode.
So still not “Words With Friends,” the scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave an American Airlines jet publicly for refusing to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops still need to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) is responsible for regulating telephone calls, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a safety expert on national traffic issues on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not just because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that airborne transmission can also interfere with transmitting towers," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA to loosen restrictions on use has increased.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, up to one-third of passengers forget or ignore turning off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travellers in 1966 after reports of interference with navigation and communication devices by passenger-carrying FM radios became known, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA to disturb electronic interference.
Airlines have been providing passengers with Wi-Fi for several years when the flight altitude has been reached.
The airplanes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the stronger use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit far less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal radiation when you scroll around.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the advocates of easing restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees invited a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and took a test flight to identify problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he felt the interference from the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots speaking for aircraft systems to be disrupted by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the FAA recommended that pilots be allowed to order the aircraft to be shut down by passengers when instrument landing in poor visibility.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adaptation for travelers who today would be extensively equipped with technology.
“We are delighted that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not in conflict with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
