Scientists were able to shed more light on the relationship between a dog’s tail wagging and his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs respond to their peers’ lateral tails, the researchers monitored the animals as they watched these films from other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
Probably we will soon understand why the tail moves in one direction, sometimes in the other
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a true-to-life version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the waving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail inclination was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog waving), their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience what movements they should be concerned about and when they should not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wedging with the tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side produces less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers to better understand their pet’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog, and to the right when looking at a satisfied dog.
Another research at the University of Victoria in Canada stated: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robotic dog when its ‘tail’ is waving to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming restless – exactly the opposite of what was done in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could stem from the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
"While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined - and dogs are no exception," Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior is easy to record, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
