I recognize the great and versatile things Obama has accomplished, from the adoption of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the forced secrecy of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I also believe that the party-political blockade tactics have tilted too many aspirations to advance our nation: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance, and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after I have defended the Obama administration countless times against colleagues and acquaintances, I have reached the end of my attempts to explain.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it allows for the interception of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It can’t explain why the National Security Agency collects data about Americans’ privacy and why whistleblowers who disclose state wrongdoing are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why the public funding and spending limits were circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the results of a report saying that the White House’s efforts to bring the media to a standstill were the “most aggressive... since the Nixon government.”
And most recently, it cannot apologize for the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at the age of 18 that government work could contradict its preceding political campaigns.
Obviously, the deputy name is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and accidental events such as the Newtown Massacre shape public debate.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to have been largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and uneven alternative, he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from pressure from future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of so long.
But with Obama’s approval ratings falling to below 45% this week, returning to 2008 has become all the harder with this book.
