On the way through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle Brings Free Medical Assistance to Remote Villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend nearly every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to vote for him as “CNN Hero of the Year”.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father lose consciousness over and over again and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but then an inflammation developed, which spread to his brain and caused a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet you are not the first.
There are many patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwell's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, in the United States, the ratio is for a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country’s healthcare spending is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and provides free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and drive with the strapped medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed like heroes: a feast, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and wave – with its wide smiles and limitless energy – is happy to attend the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team will start examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document that is required for school but many poor families simply can’t afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operation and the disinfection equipment is powered by the group’s generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It’s a strenuous pensum, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’re drumming all night long so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free operation of a groin fracture he received now allows him to work again.
“This will change the future of my family,” the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in her second year and volunteers in Bwell's group.
He’s always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
“We can be there for surgeries where we can help dodge blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
That would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and instruction.
"He's definitely a hero," O'Malley says.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives and thus fulfilling a promise he made to his father brings him great joy.
“I am so happy when I do this work,” says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website and learn how you can help.
