Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At about 120 meters in length, a sewage canal from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
Anyone who visits Cologne will not pass by the cathedral.
The two towers rise to the sky at around 157 metres, making it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers know that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the underworld of Cologne.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore of the remnants of the old city walls, only that which was not too large remained.
For this reason, most users of the car park today also rush past the Roman remains and only park their cars.
But those who take a closer look will discover an archaeological site separated by metal lattice bars in the parking deck D2.
You can see about five meters high ruins of hand-plate-sized stones.
"They are remnants of the Roman city walls, which were built in the second half of the first century after Christ," says Schulze.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look into a dark, 15 meter deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately hardly noticed.
Next stop of the tour is the pretorium, and here the participants descend again into the depths.
Here we experience the headquarters of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the pretor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means as much as "city of Roman law and city of Agrippinenser, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult".
And the pretorium is the former governor’s palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the entrance hall of the exhibition, a tunnel leads to the Roman sewage canal, which is here preserved over a length of about 120 meters.
"You can quietly walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers the guests up.
Schulze has a surprise.
After he gets the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16 meter deep, walkable shaft.
"We are now in the Mikveh, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater, which was essential for the ritual washes.
To this day, in the lower end of the Mikveh, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikveh will be part of an archaeological zone on the Town Hall Square, for which construction work will begin shortly.
However, it will take a few more years to complete.
