John Kerry says in an unprecedented admission that U.S. espionage has gone “unreasonably too far”
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, hinted at a softening of the U.S.’s defensive stance on its surveillance programs, saying that espionage had gone “unreasonably too far in certain cases.”
The Secretary of State also admitted that he, along with Barack Obama, bears the responsibility for switching to “autopilot” when the explosive disclosures by whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s espionage activities became public.
Through the leaked information, the U.S. government has fallen into a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
In a video-recorded speech at the Open Government conference in London, Kerry said: “Without a doubt, the President and I, as well as others in the government, have learned of some things that were almost autopiloted simply because of the ability to do so, which dates back to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War, as well as, of course, to 9/11.”
He was the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, “In some cases, this has gone too far inappropriately.”
The President is determined to clarify and therefore conducts a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here.
I assure you that the rights of innocent people in this process will not be compromised.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force of good and that many lives had been saved through its surveillance operations.
He added: “We are dealing with a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up.”
There is radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we have learned of such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about alleged U.S. espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue working with the U.S. on anti-terrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
