"It is very important for the national security interests of the United States that Europeans remain on board in view of our joint efforts against terrorism," Murphy, who sits in the Senate for the first time as a Democrat and serves as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, said in an interview in Washington.
I am also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their anger about the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has captured millions of telephone data in Europe have burdened relations with some U.S. allies, although the head of the intelligence agency this week said the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations cited from documents passed by Snowden, according to which the NSA had monitored the cell phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
National intelligence chief James Clapper defended espionage among allies as necessary, declaring that it was common practice on both sides.
In all the turmoil, Murphy said his agency was preparing the Congressional trip to take place this year, hoping the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
